From the archive. Ray Gun 46, Supergrass Feature: Opening Double Page Spread. Published in April '97. Gaz Coombes photographed by Julie Sleaford. The article coincided with the release of their second album titled 'In It For The Money', which was one that got continuous plays from me in the Ray Gun office throughout '97. A fantastic record. The interview for this article took place in a pub called 'The Slaughtered Pig' in their hometown of Oxford, England - and the title that I got from the writer (Ken Micallef) was 'Private Life' which spoke to the public spotlight aspect of being in a band - which they all detested. Julie's image was incredible, a designers dream in my opinion and I really enjoyed the challenge of combining typography with it. The crisp and clean nature of the photograph pushed me to create some simple, sharp typography - so I set all the elements on screen, printed them out, and scanned them back in so that they were malleable. I then did a simple typographic-play on the 'Private Life' title of the feature - by reversing and flipping most of it to create some abstraction and distance from the viewer, as well as trying to create some interaction between Gaz's lean and the headline type. I then added a little uneasiness by step-and-repeating a few of the characters. I pretty much spent my 18 months on Ray Gun listening to this album, 'Ultra', 'This Is Hardcore', 'Blur', Urban Hymns' and New Order's catalogue. my review: First, your poster is wonderful. It communicates the issue without any words, always a challenge that you mastered beautifully. Second, about copying other people's work: Apart for the obvious moral issue, when a designer takes work from someone else, that person is depriving him/herself of one of the most lovely experiences one can have as a designer: To be the parent of a piece of work. Even if nobody ever detects that its borrowed from someone else, the borrower will always know. And so that person will never become the parent, always remain the babysitter. And as the babysitter one will never be able to care for the baby, to nurture and push it, as well as a parent could. ‚†Ä
